      86                 :            : // This struct describes the internal layout of the message, hence this is
      87                 :            : // used to act on the message reflectively.
      88                 :            : //   default_instance:  The default instance of the message.  This is only
      89                 :            : //                  used to obtain pointers to default instances of embedded
      90                 :            : //                  messages, which GetMessage() will return if the particular
      91                 :            : //                  sub-message has not been initialized yet.  (Thus, all
      92                 :            : //                  embedded message fields *must* have non-NULL pointers
      93                 :            : //                  in the default instance.)
      94                 :            : //   offsets:       An array of ints giving the byte offsets.
      95                 :            : //                  For each oneof or weak field, the offset is relative to the
      96                 :            : //                  default_instance. These can be computed at compile time
      97                 :            : //                  using the
      98                 :            : //                  GOOGLE_PROTOBUF_GENERATED_DEFAULT_ONEOF_FIELD_OFFSET()
      99                 :            : //                  macro. For each none oneof field, the offset is related to
     100                 :            : //                  the start of the message object.  These can be computed at
     101                 :            : //                  compile time using the
     102                 :            : //                  GOOGLE_PROTOBUF_GENERATED_MESSAGE_FIELD_OFFSET() macro.
     103                 :            : //                  Besides offsets for all fields, this array also contains
     104                 :            : //                  offsets for oneof unions. The offset of the i-th oneof union
     105                 :            : //                  is offsets[descriptor->field_count() + i].
     106                 :            : //   has_bit_indices:  Mapping from field indexes to their index in the has
     107                 :            : //                  bit array.
     108                 :            : //   has_bits_offset:  Offset in the message of an array of uint32s of size
     109                 :            : //                  descriptor->field_count()/32, rounded up.  This is a
     110                 :            : //                  bitfield where each bit indicates whether or not the
     111                 :            : //                  corresponding field of the message has been initialized.
     112                 :            : //                  The bit for field index i is obtained by the expression:
     113                 :            : //                    has_bits[i / 32] & (1 << (i % 32))
     114                 :            : //   unknown_fields_offset:  Offset in the message of the UnknownFieldSet for
     115                 :            : //                  the message.
     116                 :            : //   extensions_offset:  Offset in the message of the ExtensionSet for the
     117                 :            : //                  message, or -1 if the message type has no extension
     118                 :            : //                  ranges.
     119                 :            : //   oneof_case_offset:  Offset in the message of an array of uint32s of
     120                 :            : //                  size descriptor->oneof_decl_count().  Each uint32
     121                 :            : //                  indicates what field is set for each oneof.
     122                 :            : //   object_size:   The size of a message object of this type, as measured
     123                 :            : //                  by sizeof().
     124                 :            : //   arena_offset:  If a message doesn't have a unknown_field_set that stores
     125                 :            : //                  the arena, it must have a direct pointer to the arena.
     126                 :            : //   weak_field_map_offset: If the message proto has weak fields, this is the
     127                 :            : //                  offset of _weak_field_map_ in the generated proto. Otherwise
     128                 :            : //                  -1.

     234                 :            : // THIS CLASS IS NOT INTENDED FOR DIRECT USE.  It is intended for use
     235                 :            : // by generated code.  This class is just a big hack that reduces code
     236                 :            : // size.
     237                 :            : //
     238                 :            : // A GeneratedMessageReflection is an implementation of Reflection
     239                 :            : // which expects all fields to be backed by simple variables located in
     240                 :            : // memory.  The locations are given using a base pointer and a set of
     241                 :            : // offsets.
     242                 :            : //
     243                 :            : // It is required that the user represents fields of each type in a standard
     244                 :            : // way, so that GeneratedMessageReflection can cast the void* pointer to
     245                 :            : // the appropriate type.  For primitive fields and string fields, each field
     246                 :            : // should be represented using the obvious C++ primitive type.  Enums and
     247                 :            : // Messages are different:
     248                 :            : //  - Singular Message fields are stored as a pointer to a Message.  These
     249                 :            : //    should start out NULL, except for in the default instance where they
     250                 :            : //    should start out pointing to other default instances.
     251                 :            : //  - Enum fields are stored as an int.  This int must always contain
     252                 :            : //    a valid value, such that EnumDescriptor::FindValueByNumber() would
     253                 :            : //    not return NULL.
     254                 :            : //  - Repeated fields are stored as RepeatedFields or RepeatedPtrFields
     255                 :            : //    of whatever type the individual field would be.  Strings and
     256                 :            : //    Messages use RepeatedPtrFields while everything else uses
     257                 :            : //    RepeatedFields.

     636                 :            : // There are some places in proto2 where dynamic_cast would be useful as an
     637                 :            : // optimization.  For example, take Message::MergeFrom(const Message& other).
     638                 :            : // For a given generated message FooMessage, we generate these two methods:
     639                 :            : //   void MergeFrom(const FooMessage& other);
     640                 :            : //   void MergeFrom(const Message& other);
     641                 :            : // The former method can be implemented directly in terms of FooMessage's
     642                 :            : // inline accessors, but the latter method must work with the reflection
     643                 :            : // interface.  However, if the parameter to the latter method is actually of
     644                 :            : // type FooMessage, then we'd like to be able to just call the other method
     645                 :            : // as an optimization.  So, we use dynamic_cast to check this.
     646                 :            : //
     647                 :            : // That said, dynamic_cast requires RTTI, which many people like to disable
     648                 :            : // for performance and code size reasons.  When RTTI is not available, we
     649                 :            : // still need to produce correct results.  So, in this case we have to fall
     650                 :            : // back to using reflection, which is what we would have done anyway if the
     651                 :            : // objects were not of the exact same class.
     652                 :            : //
     653                 :            : // dynamic_cast_if_available() implements this logic.  If RTTI is
     654                 :            : // enabled, it does a dynamic_cast.  If RTTI is disabled, it just returns
     655                 :            : // NULL.
     656                 :            : //
     657                 :            : // If you need to compile without RTTI, simply #define GOOGLE_PROTOBUF_NO_RTTI.
     658                 :            : // On MSVC, this should be detected automatically.
     659                 :            : template<typename To, typename From>
     660                 :            : inline To dynamic_cast_if_available(From from) {
     661                 :            : #if defined(GOOGLE_PROTOBUF_NO_RTTI) || (defined(_MSC_VER)&&!defined(_CPPRTTI))
     662                 :            :   // Avoid the compiler warning about unused variables.
     663                 :            :   (void)from;
     664                 :            :   return NULL;
     665                 :            : #else
     666                 :            :   return dynamic_cast<To>(from);
     667                 :            : #endif
     668                 :            : }
